SIMPLE: moneyer
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Moneyer
<hw>Mon"ey*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Money</er>; cf. OF. <ets>monoier</ets>, F. <ets>monnoayeur</ets>, L.
<ets>monetarius</ets> a master of the mint. Cf.
<er>Monetary</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A person who deals in money;
banker or broker.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An authorized coiner of money.</def> <rj><au>Sir M.
Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The Company of Moneyers</b></col>, <cd>the officials who
formerly coined the money of Great Britain, and who claimed certain
prescriptive rights and privileges.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>moneylender</ent>⟦br⟧
